definition.value: Food material chopped into roughly bite-sized pieces.
A seed of a jack seed plant (Canavalia ensiformis).
A pigeon pea food product is a food product derived from the pigeon pea plant
A seed of a pigeon pea plant (Cajanus cajan).
A soybean pod is a dry or raw bean pod of the soybean plant.
A seed of a marrow bean plant which is a varietal of a common bean plant (Phaseolus vulgaris).
Marrow beans are plump white beans with a creamy texture.  These beans were popular in the U.S. in the 1850's as a baking bean. They have the flavor of bacon and work well pureed for soup.
A seed of a  velvet bean plant (Mucuna pruriens)

Red bananas are a group of varieties of banana with reddish-purple skin. Some are smaller and plumper than the common Cavendish banana, others much larger.
A potato substance is a whole potato transformed into some derivative food material. It doesn't include potato food products that are ready to consume or simply require thawing or reheating.
A chicken egg which has been boiled, but may be hard boiled or soft boiled, and may have its shell on or off.

Banana powder is a powder made from processed bananas. It is used as a component for production of milk shakes and baby foods. It is also used in the manufacture of various types of cakes and biscuits.
A snow pea pod is a pea pod from a snow pea plant.
A whole turkey food product consists of the plucked carcass of a turkey with head and entrails removed and with organ meats and neck severed and possibly included in body cavity.
Extra virgin olive oil is a virgin olive oil which has a free acidity, expressed as oleic acid, of not more than 0.8 grams per 100 grams.
Edamame is a preparation of immature soybeans in their pods, or with the pod removed. It originates in East Asia cuisine. The pods or beans are boiled or steamed and may be served with salt.
Commercially immature soybeans with or without pod are often marketed as Edamame in a frozen format.
A bean pod which is still tender rather than one that has reached full maturity.

Ikejime is a method of slaughtering fish to maintain the quality of its meat. The technique originated in Japan, but is now in widespread use. It involves the insertion of a spike quickly and directly into the hindbrain, usually located slightly behind and above the eye, thereby causing immediate brain death.

When spiked correctly, the fish fins flare and the fish relaxes, immediately ceasing all motion. Destroying the brain and the spinal cord of the fish will prevent reflex action from happening; such muscle movements would otherwise consume adenosine triphosphate (ATP) in the muscle, and as a result produce lactic acid and ammonia, making the fish sour, soggy and less tasteful. Furthermore, the blood contained in the fish flesh retracts to the gut cavity, which produces a better coloured and flavoured fillet, and prolongs shelf life. [Wikipedia]
A liver food product is a food product that derives from one or more liver organs.
A lung food product is a food product that derivers from one or more mammalian lungs.
A raw lung that is obtained from a sheep.
A whole raw lung is a whole lung organ obtained from an animal during a butchery process.
A raw kidney that is obtained from a lamb.
A whole raw lamb kidney is a whole raw kidney obtained from a lamb during a butchery process.

Haggis is a savoury pudding containing sheep's pluck (heart, liver, and lungs); minced with onion, oatmeal, suet, spices, and salt, mixed with stock, and cooked while traditionally encased in the animal's stomach though now often in an artificial casing instead.
